"1. Use LensKit version 0.14.4 and implement exactly three recommenders: ALS, ItemKNN, and Pop, using LensKit\u2019s standard/default hyperparameters unless explicitly required by the library for implicit-feedback training.\n2. Load the three raw datasets from the working directory using these exact filenames: MovieLens100K from `u.data`, Amazon Video Games from `VideoGames.csv`, and Last.FM from `UserTaggedArtists-timestamps.dat`.\n3. Parse each dataset correctly into user\u2013item interaction records with dataset-specific schemas: MovieLens100K tab-separated `user item rating timestamp`; Amazon Video Games CSV with user, item, rating fields; Last.FM tab-separated artist-tag events where user\u2013artist pairs must be extracted as implicit interactions.\n4. Preprocess each dataset with iterative 5-core filtering on the final implicit interaction graph, ensuring every retained user and every retained item has at least 5 interactions.\n5. Convert MovieLens100K and Amazon Video Games to implicit feedback by keeping only interactions with rating > 3; discard ratings <= 3 before 5-core filtering.\n6. Treat Last.FM as implicit feedback directly; collapse repeated user\u2013artist events to a single interaction per user\u2013item pair unless the chosen LensKit implicit pipeline explicitly requires counts, in which case document and use a consistent count-based representation.\n7. Generate exactly 5 distinct random seeds for data splitting, record them, and reuse the same seed set across all datasets and algorithms.\n8. For each dataset and seed, perform a user-based 80/20 holdout split so that each eligible user has approximately 80% of interactions in train and 20% in test, with randomization controlled only by the current seed.\n9. Ensure the split is valid for top-N evaluation: every test user must retain at least 1 test interaction and enough training history to fit/evaluate; handle users with too few interactions after filtering/splitting deterministically and report any exclusions.\n10. Train each algorithm separately on every dataset-seed training split and generate top-N recommendations for the corresponding test users, excluding items seen in the user\u2019s training data.\n11. Evaluate recommendation accuracy with nDCG@1, nDCG@5, nDCG@10 and Precision@1, Precision@5, Precision@10 using the held-out test interactions as relevant items.\n12. Aggregate metrics at the user level within each dataset-algorithm-seed run, then compute run-level summary statistics (at minimum mean; preferably also standard deviation or standard error across users).\n13. Produce a final results table covering all 3 datasets \u00d7 3 algorithms \u00d7 5 seeds, with one row per run or an equivalent tidy format containing dataset, algorithm, seed, and all six metric values.\n14. Quantify seed sensitivity by summarizing, for each dataset-algorithm pair, the variation across the 5 split seeds for every metric (e.g., mean, standard deviation, min/max, and/or coefficient of variation).\n15. Conduct a short statistical analysis across seeds for each dataset-algorithm pair, such as confidence intervals over the 5 seed-level results and/or a simple repeated comparison of variance/range, and clearly state that the analysis concerns split-seed variability rather than algorithm superiority.\n16. Preserve reproducibility by setting random seeds explicitly for all randomized operations, logging software/library versions, and saving intermediate filtered dataset sizes and split sizes.\n17. Include robust checks for malformed rows, duplicate interactions, and schema mismatches so the script runs without errors on the provided raw files.\n18. Output concise experiment artifacts suitable for reporting: filtered dataset statistics, per-seed evaluation metrics, across-seed variability summaries, and a brief textual interpretation of how much split random seeds affect accuracy."